Market Challenges
Data Gaps and Methodological Complexity

Despite growing interest, the United States HEOR for Gene Therapy Pricing Market faces significant challenges in capturing long‑term effectiveness data. Limited enrollment in post‑approval registries and methodological uncertainties around extrapolating survival benefits hinder precise economic modeling.

Other Challenges

Limited Long‑Term Real‑World Evidence
The scarcity of longitudinal patient outcomes restricts the ability to validate cost‑effectiveness models, creating hesitation among payers when authorizing high‑priced gene therapies.

Market Restraints
Regulatory Uncertainty around Pricing Models

Regulatory bodies have yet to establish clear guidelines for value‑based pricing of gene therapies, leading to cautious adoption by payers. This uncertainty acts as a restraint on the full potential of HEOR‑driven pricing strategies in the United States.

The high upfront cost of manufacturing viral vectors continues to inflate price tags, making it difficult for payers to justify reimbursement without definitive health‑economic proof.

Additionally, state‑by‑state variation in Medicaid formularies creates inconsistent reimbursement frameworks, further limiting market expansion.

